<bdy>

<b>Operating system development</b> refers to the development of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../194/22194.xml">
operating systems</link>, and it is often abbreviated to <b>OSDev</b>.
<sec>
<st>
 Development </st>

<p>

Elements of traditional PC based operating systems include: </p>
<p>

<list>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../394/50394.xml">
Kernel</link>:</entry>
<entry level="2" type="bullet">

 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../679/6885679.xml">
Bootstrapping</link></entry>
<entry level="2" type="bullet">

 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../924/66924.xml">
Memory management</link></entry>
<entry level="2" type="bullet">

 In the case of a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../126/20126.xml">
multitasking</link> operating system, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../191/1655191.xml">
 task management</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../920/231920.xml">
scheduling</link></entry>
<entry level="2" type="bullet">

 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../101/9101.xml">
Device driver</link> management</entry>
</list>
</p>
<p>

Traditionally, kernel developers have commonly used the <programming_language wordnetid="106898352" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../021/6021.xml">
C programming language</link></programming_language>
 and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../368/1368.xml">
Assembly</link>. As history has shown, low-level languages are gradually replaced by <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../842/189842.xml">
high-level languages</link> as the processing power of computers increases. C, however, remains the favorite for most OS developers, as it provides low-level pointer manipulation and requires no run-time support (as opposed to some elements of <programming_language wordnetid="106898352" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../038/72038.xml">
C++</link></programming_language>
, such as the new and delete operators).</p>

